article.description: The Sun earned home court throughout the WNBA playoffs with a win over the Mystics on Friday.
article.headline: Sun have home court through WNBA playoffs
article.linkText: Sun knock out Mystics, earn home court
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Nykesha Sales scored 20 points and Taj
McWilliams-Franklin added 18 points and 10 rebounds as the
Connecticut Sun blew out the Washington Mystics 81-47 Friday night
to earn home-court advantage throughout the WNBA playoffs.

Connecticut (25-8), which owns the tiebreaker over Sacramento
after sweeping the season series, can do no worse than tie the
Monarchs for best record in the league, thus securing home court.
The loss eliminated Washington (15-18) from the playoffs.

Lindsay Whalen had 17 points and four assists for Connecticut,
which rebounded from consecutive losses to New York and Indiana.
DeLisha Milton-Jones led the Mystics with 11 points.

As top seed in the Eastern Conference, the Sun will play No. 4
Detroit next week in the best-of-three conference semifinals.
Detroit won three of the four games played between the teams this
season.

The Sun also tied a WNBA record for most regular-season wins by
an Eastern Conference team, matching Detroit's mark from 2003. The
Sun can set the record with a win Saturday in the regular-season
finale at Charlotte.

The Sun clinched the Eastern Conference title on Aug. 14.

Connecticut trailed 20-18 with less than 11 minutes left in the
first half before taking control with a 24-2 surge and held an 18-point edge at the break.

Washington missed 20 of its last 24 shots in the first half.
